Particularly noteworthy is Point 2 of the agreement, a public bilateral commitment to cease permanently economically motivated cyber-espionage. Through this agreement between the most prevalent target of economic espionage and arguably the most notorious perpetrator they sent an important signal to third countries, explicitly distinguishing acceptable from not-acceptable state behavior. Significantly, the PRC government acknowledged for the first time the legitimacy of the prohibition of economic cyber-espionage when stating that “the Chinese government will not, in whatever form, engage in commercial theft or encourage or support such attempts by anyone.”^{73} Moreover, after the first meeting of the new US-Sino cyber-dialogue in December 2015 Xinhua News agency reported that the group had discussed alleged theft of data of the U.S. Office of Personnel Management by Chinese hackers, noting that „through investigation, the case turned out to be a criminal case rather than a state-sponsored cyber attack as the U.S side has previously suspected”, thereby acknowledging that an offensive cyber-operation had occurred from Chinese territory.^{74}

While Chinese compliance with the accord rescinded in 2017, the two governments reaffirmed their commitment to “further solidifying, developing, and maintaining the Dialogue mechanism and continuing to strengthen bilateral cooperation in cybersecurity” in the framework of the third US-China joint dialogue on cyber-crime at the end of 2016.^{75}

Notably, the US-China agreement also fertilized similar undertakings between China and other democratic countries: a similar agreement was reached between Great Britain and China, but Germany and China have been unable to settle their discord.^{76} However, in November 2015, the G20 followed suit, including Russia, in accepting the norm against conducting or supporting economically motivated cyber-espionage.^{77}
